# Git push: `origin` (main repo) vs `backup` (mirror repo)

This repo has two remotes:

| Remote | Repository |
|--------|------------|
| `origin` | `git@github.com:ki-bay/kibay.com.do.git` |
| `backup` | `git@github.com:ki-bay/kibay.com.do-backup.git` |

The user wants **one target per request** unless they explicitly ask for both.

## When the user asks to push to **backup** (“push to backup”, “backup only”, “sync backup”)

- Push **only** to the `backup` remote. **Do not** push to `origin`.
- Typical command (local branch `main` → backup repo’s `main`):  
  `git push backup main`
- If they use another local branch, push that branch name instead (e.g. `git push backup feature/foo:main` only if they ask).

## When the user asks to push to **main** / default push (“push to main”, “push”, “deploy”, “ship it” — **without** saying backup)

- Push **only** to `origin`:  
  `git push origin main`  
- **Do not** push to `backup` unless they also asked to update the backup.

## Both targets

Only push to **both** remotes if the user clearly asks (e.g. “push main and backup”, “push to both repos”).

## Before pushing

- Run `git remote -v` and `git branch` if the branch or remote is unclear.
- Never `git push --force` unless the user explicitly requests it and understands the risk.
